From: stopless-java-gc <noreply@anthropic.com>
Subject: [PATCH 0064/N] copy_aarch64.hpp: pd_fill_to_words honours HeapWord=16 under purecap

`pd_fill_to_words` casts `HeapWord*` to `julong*` (8-byte) and writes
`count` julongs. On standard LP64 with `HeapWord=8`, this writes
`count * 8 = count * HeapWordSize` bytes — correct.

Under CHERI purecap with our patch 0060 setting `HeapWord=16`, this
under-writes the buffer by half (writes `count*8` bytes, caller
expected `count*16`). Downstream allocators that rely on the buffer
being zero see garbage in the upper 8 bytes of every HeapWord, which
shows up as bogus cap fields or invalid vtable pointers — manifesting
as SIGSEGV deep in class init (e.g., inside String load when an
uninitialised cap-typed field is dereferenced via memset).

Fix: compute the julong write count as `count * sizeof(HeapWord) /
sizeof(julong)`. On standard LP64 this is `count * 1 = count`
(no change). On purecap this is `count * 2` (correct).

This is the same bug pattern as the SIMD-stride miscompute in 0059:
HotSpot conflates `wordSize == HeapWordSize == sizeof(julong) == 8`
in many places. We are unwinding those conflations one at a time as
they surface at runtime.

Refs: docs/05_zgc_cheri_collision_report.md (patch 0064)

--- a/src/hotspot/cpu/aarch64/copy_aarch64.hpp
+++ b/src/hotspot/cpu/aarch64/copy_aarch64.hpp
@@ -29,8 +29,11 @@
 #include OS_CPU_HEADER(copy)

 static void pd_fill_to_words(HeapWord* tohw, size_t count, juint value) {
+  // Write count HeapWords. HeapWord may be 8 (standard LP64) or 16 (CHERI
+  // purecap). Compute julong count from HeapWord count.
   julong* to = (julong*) tohw;
   julong  v  = ((julong) value << 32) | value;
+  count = count * (sizeof(HeapWord) / sizeof(julong));
   while (count-- > 0) {
     *to++ = v;
   }
